{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}
{{Use Indian English|date=June 2018}}
{{italic title}}
'''''Hans''''' is a [[Hindi]] [[wikt:Monthly|monthly]] literary magazine published from [[Delhi]]. The magazine was first started by pioneer of modern Hindi literature [[Premchand]] in 1930, and revived in 1986 by [[Rajendra Yadav]], a noted short-story writer and novelist.<ref>{{cite web|title=Of Hans and a flight for a cause|work=The Hindu|url= http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/of-hans-and-a-flight-for-a-cause/article4558056.ece|date=28 March 2013|accessdate=27 March 2014|author= Kuldeep Kumar}}</ref>

In 1930,<ref name=pubp>{{cite news|author1=Bree Turner|title=The Birth, Death, Rebirth of India’s Hans Hindi Literary Magazine|url=http://publishingperspectives.com/2015/09/the-birth-death-rebirth-of-hans-the-top-hindi-literary-magazine/|accessdate=26 October 2015|work=Publishing Perspective|date=9 September 2015}}</ref> ''Hans'' began publication under the editorship of [[Premchand]]. [[Mahatma Gandhi]] and [[K. M. Munshi]]. They were associated with ''Hans'' to provide an impetus to creative writing. It became a forum projecting national problems and encouraged socially relevant fiction during the struggle for Indian independence. 

In 1936 Hans ceased publication following the death of Premchand.<ref name=pubp/> The magazine was revived in 1986 with [[Rajendra Yadav]] as editor.<ref>[http://www.hinduonnet.com/fline/fl2213/stories/20050701002109200.htm Journals of resurgence] Frontline, ''The Hindu'', 1 July 2005.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Swan's song: Celebrating 25 years of a landmark Hindi literary magazine|url=http://www.livemint.com/2011/12/27210710/Swan8217s-song.html|work=Mint|date=27 December 2011}}</ref>

